GeneralInfo.ExecutiveSummary:
{tf1 bidis\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{ onttbl{ 0 roman prq2 charset0 Times New Roman;}{ 1 nil prq2 charset2 WP MathA;}{ 2 nil charset0 Tahoma;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\ltrpar 0 s24 Mitsui Chemicals, Inc. has submitted a study investigating the metabolism of an equimolar mixture of [tetrahydrofuran-\super 14
osupersub C]dinotefuran and [guanidine-\super 14
osupersub C]dinotefuran in apples. One apple tree each received a single postemergence foliar spray of the test substance, formulated as a 20% water-dispersible granule (WDG) formulation, at 0.179 lb ai/A or at 1.79 lb ai/A. Mature apples were collected from both trees 21 days after treatment; leaf samples were collected immediately following application and at apple harvest. The in-life phase of the study was conducted by Research for Hire (Porterville CA), and the analytical phase was conducted by Ricerca, LLC (Painesville, OH).\par \par The TRR were 0.153 ppm in whole apples and 10.769 ppm in leaves harvested 21 days following application of [\super 14
osupersub C]dinotefuran at 0.179 lb ai/A. In apples harvested 21 days following treatment at 1.79 lb ai/A, TRR were 1.924 ppm in whole apples and 117.68 ppm in leaves. TRR values in whole apples were calculated by summing the radioactivity in water surface washes, apple juice, and apple pomace. The petitioner noted that the relatively low TRR in apples versus leaves suggests limited translocation of dinotefuran from foliage to fruit.\par \par The distribution of radioactive residues in apples from the low- and high-dose applications was similar. The water surface wash removed  1 - 0 62-69% TRR from whole apples, and apple juice collected following homogenization and centrifugation of rinsed apples accounted for  1 - 0 21-28% TRR. The apple pomace remaining following centrifugation was subjected to extraction with methanol/water, which removed  1 - 0 6-8% TRR, leaving nonextractable residues of  1 - 0 2-3% TRR. \par \par Parent dinotefuran was the major residue identified, accounting for 28.8% TRR (0.044 ppm) in low-dose apples and 32.9% TRR (0.633 ppm) in high-dose apples. The petitioner noted that the majority of dinotefuran ( 1 - 0 25-28% TRR) was identified in the surface wash, suggesting that most of the applied dinotefuran remained on the surface of the fruit. Three metabolites were also identified as significant residues in low- and high-dose apples, respectively: (i) UF at 20.0% and 20.9% TRR (0.031 and 0.403 ppm); (ii) DN at 10.4% and 6.9% TRR (0.016 and 0.134 ppm); and (iii) PHP at 13.5% and 13.2% TRR (0.021 and 0.254 ppm). Metabolites UF-DO, NG, MNG, 446-DO, BCDN, and FNG were identified individually at levels of 1.2-3.6% TRR in apples from both dose levels. The remainder of the radioactivity consisted of up to six polar unknowns.\par \par Based on the submitted study, dinotefuran was extensively metabolized in apples. The petitioner has concluded that metabolism in apples proceeds by the following reactions: (i) hydrolysis of the nitroimino moiety to form UF; (ii) loss of the nitro group to form DN; (iii) intramolecular ring formation to form PHP and BCDN; (iv) tetrahydrofuran ring hydroxylation and ring opening to form UF-DO and 446-DO; (v) loss of the tetrahydrofuran portion of the molecule to form MNG, and subsequent N-demethylation to form NG; and (vi) N-demethylation of dinotefuran to form FNG.\par \pard\ltrpar 2 s16\par }

Sampling.Description: {\rtf1\fbidis\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\froman\fprq2\fcharset0 Times New Roman;}{\f1\fnil\fcharset0 Tahoma;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\ltrpar\tx0\f0\fs24 Apple leaf samples were ground in dry ice and total radioactive residues (TRR) were determined in triplicate subsamples by combustion/LSC; leaf samples were not further extracted for metabolite characterization. \par \par Apple samples were surface washed with water, then cut into small pieces and homogenized. The homogenate was centrifuged (3x), and the supernatant (apple juice) was filtered and reserved for HPLC analysis. The pellet (pomace) was ground in dry ice and subjected to extraction with methanol:water (70:30, v:v; 3x) followed by vacuum filtration. The extracts were combined, concentrated by rotary evaporation, and reserved for HPLC analysis. The resulting nonextractable residues were not subjected to further extraction/analysis. The TRR in triplicate subsamples of apple pomace and nonextractable residues were determined by combustion/LSC, and TRR in duplicate or triplicate aliquots of surface washes, juice, and pomace extracts were determined by LSC. The reported limit of detection for LSC determinations was 0.0024 ppm. TRR in whole apple fruit was calculated by summation of the radioactivity in the surface wash, juice, and pomace. \par \par The extraction procedures for apples are summarized in the flow charts below, which were copied without alteration from MRID 45639804.\par \pard\ltrpar\f1\fs16\par }

ExtractionAndAnalysis.StrategiesDescription: {\rtf1\fbidis\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\froman\fprq2\fcharset0 Times New Roman;}{\f1\fnil\fprq2\fcharset0 WP TypographicSymbols;}{\f2\fnil\fcharset0 Tahoma;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\ltrpar\fi-720\li720\tx0\b\f0\fs24 Analytical Methodology\b0\par \pard\ltrpar\tx0\par Samples of the surface washes, apple juice, and pomace extracts were analyzed by HPLC using a system equipped with a Waters Sugiyama L-Column ODS, a Zorbax C18 guard column, a UV detector at 240 nm, and a flow-through radioactivity detector. A gradient mobile phase of 4.5 mM NH\sub 4\nosupersub OH:5 mM nonafluorovaleric acid in water, pH 3.5, changing to 5 mM nonafluorovaleric acid in methanol was used. This system was used to identify and quantitate the following metabolites in washes, juice, and pomace extracts: MTI-446, PHP, 446-DO, UF, BCDN, DN, UF-DO, and FNG.\par \par To quantitate metabolites NG and MNG, which eluted as unresolved peaks in the initial HPLC analysis, subsamples were analyzed on a similar HPLC system using a gradient mobile phase of water changing to acetonitrile (both containing 0.1% trifluoroacetic acid) and fraction collection. The fraction containing NG and MNG was isolated and concentrated to dryness, then subjected to acid hydrolysis with 1.0 N HCl (at 40 C for 16 hours) to release any conjugated metabolites. The resulting hydrolysate was evaporated to dryness, redissolved in water and subjected to TLC analysis using silica gel 60 LK6DF plates, a solvent system of chloroform:methanol (8:2, v:v) radioanalytical imaging, and UV light and/or iodine crystals for visualization of nonlabeled standards.\par \par Metabolites were initially identified by retention time comparisons with reference standards. Identification of metabolites isolated from apple juice was confirmed by co-chromatography with reference standards and by LC/MS. TLC analysis with iodine visualization was used to confirm the identification of BCDN isolated from juice. The following reference standards were used: \par \f1 $\f0 dinotefuran\par \f1 $\f0 446-DO [1-[4-hydroxy-2-(hydroxymethyl)butyl]-3-methyl-2-nitroguanidine]\par \f1 $\f0 BCDN succinate [3-(methylamino)-9-oxa-2-aza-4-azoniabicyclo[4.3.0]non-3-ene hydrogen succinate]\par \f1 $\f0 MNG [1-methyl-2-nitroguanidine]\par \f1 $\f0 NG [nitroguanidine]\par \f1 $\f0 PHP [6-hydroxy-5-(2-hydroxyethyl)-1-methyl-1,3-diazinane-2-ylidene-\i N\i0 -nitroamine]\par \f1 $\f0 MPZ [1-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl)-1,3,5-triazinane-2-ylidene-\i N-\i0 nitroamine]\par \f1 $\f0 PZ [5-(1-methylethyl)-1,3,5-triazinane-2-ylidene-\i N\i0 -nitroamine]\par \f1 $\f0 FNG [2-nitro-1-(tetrahydro-3-furylmethyl)guanidine]\par \f1 $\f0 MG hydrogen chloride [1-methylguanidinium chloride]\par \f1 $\f0 DN phosphate [1-methyl-3-(tetrahydro-3-furylmethyl)guanidinium dihydrogen phosphate]\par \f1 $\f0 UF [1-methyl-3-(tetrahydro-3-furylmethyl)urea]\par \pard\ltrpar\f2\fs16\par }
ExtractionAndAnalysis.ProceduresDescription: {\rtf1\fbidis\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\froman\fprq2\fcharset0 Times New Roman;}{\f1\fnil\fcharset0 Tahoma;}} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\ltrpar\tx0\f0\fs24 Radiolabeled reference standards of DN phosphate and UF (both labeled at the guanidine carbon) were also used, as was a dehydrated PHP standard that was prepared during the rice metabolism study.\par \par For confirmatory analyses, metabolites were isolated from apple juice from the high-dose study using open-column chromatography on a C\sub 18\nosupersub column sequentially eluted with 1% acetic acid (3x), acidified acetonitrile (ACN):water (50:50, v:v; 1% acetic acid; 3x), and ACN (3x). Like eluates were pooled, and the aqueous (1% acetic acid) and 50:50 ACN:water fractions were concentrated and subjected to HPLC analysis on a system equipped with a Zorbax SB-C18 column, a UV detector at 240 nm, and a fraction collector, and using a gradient mobile phase of water changing to methanol (each containing 0.5% formic acid). Selected metabolite zones were isolated and purified by preparative HPLC using slight modifications of this system. A subsample of the zone designated NG-MNG, which contained NG, MNG, PHP, UF-DO and a number of minor polar metabolites, was subjected to acid hydrolysis as described above, followed by further HPLC and TLC analyses.\par \par PHP had been shown to degrade to dehydrated PHP during HPLC isolation in other metabolism studies. To confirm formation of dehydrated PHP in the apple metabolism study, the isolated fraction was treated with 0.1% TFA (at 50 C for 3 hours) and subjected to HPLC co-chromatography with dehydrated PHP standard.\par \pard\ltrpar\f1\fs16\par }
